node.text: I didn’t want to post here until I felt like I’d really turned a corner. No one wants to read bad news and I don’t want to deliver it. But today was a big one for me. A little context: after my near-death scare, the fluid in my lung cavity (and general retention) ballooned me up to 256lbs and I could barely breathe. So, when I left the hospital I set two goals. 1. To get lighter than my pre-surgery weight. 2. To be able to walk ONE mile without stopping. Now it may not seem like much, because it isn’t. But today, I hit both marks. And for me, it’s a big victory on the road to recovery. In my experience there are (in general) two types of people in this world. 1) People who believe that everything is beyond their control and that they’re a victim of circumstance. 2) People who think they can control everything. Group 1 tend to become lifelong victims. Group 2 tend to feel like abysmal failures when life nut-punches them. Both types of thinking are wrong. There ARE circumstances beyond your control. It’s called life. But the constant, slow plod forward is what eventually beats it into submission. Sometimes it’s humbling (strike that, humiliating) when you have to recalibrate and change your goals. Like say, aiming for a 1300lbs total… scaled back to walking ONE mile without dying. As long as you’re moving forward, as long as you’re doing SOMEthing… you’re not a quitter. So, keep on with the baby steps. Baby steps through the office… baby steps out the door… #NameThatMovieLine #LwCSeptember

node.text: So, a brief update here: about the only thing I CAN do post-surgery (right now at the 2.5-week mark) is shoot handguns at the range. Even light recoiling rifles would be… Ill-advised. So first: to those asking, recovery is okay. It could be going better. I’ve been retaining fluid around the lungs, so everything is excruciatingly painful. Including breathing. But the good folks at Mayo have been trying at-home options to accelerate the healing process here, as the next stop would involve being re-admitted and popping in another chest tube. That would suck. Basically, people go through a lot worse, and so I’ve no right to complain. But things are pretty rough right now. SECOND: and this is what really matters to most of you… good Lord this @Waltherarms Patriot is a dream to shoot. That right there is a 100 yard shot on a 2litre Fanta with a HANDGUN!! I actually hit these shots more consistently and easily than with my 9mm carbine. That’s just not right. Shooting this gun almost feels like cheating. I’ve also run a few hundred rounds through it at this point without so much as a hiccup. So, in summary: as for right now, wherever my broken, bloated rotund body finds itself… there too will my Walther Patriot be.
